,"is_easter_egg":false,"descent_paths_to_thomas":0},"parents":{"father_id":"X02373","mother_id":"TD0138"},"marriages":[{"marriage_number":1,"spouse_id":"X02375","date_year":1856,"date_month":8,"date_day":27,"location_city":"Montpelier","location_state":"Vermont","location_country":"United States","end_type":"death_of_self","end_year":1900,"children_ids":["TD0150","TD0151","TD0152","TD0153"]}],"number_of_marriages":1,"tags":["civil_war"],"research_tags":[],"sources":[{"label":"Vermont Historical Society — Edward Dewey 8th Vermont Papers (1864)","note":"Quartermaster invoices and inventories from one year of regiment service."},{"label":"FindAGrave — Edward Dewey","url":"https://www.findagrave.com/memorial/49228431/edward_bradley-dewey"}],"research_sources":[],"notable":{"is_notable":false,"notable_category":[]},"narrative_blocks":[{"number":1,"category":"marriage","header":"Married his stepsister-in-law in 1856","body":"In August 1856 Edward married Susan Griggs Lilley — the daughter of his father Julius's third wife Susan Elizabeth Griggs Lilley (married 1855). Edward and Susan had been stepsiblings-by-marriage for one year before becoming husband and wife. They had six children, four documented in this tree."},{"number":2,"category":"military","header":"Quartermaster at Cedar Creek and Opequon","body":"Edward joined the 8th Vermont Volunteer Infantry as Lieutenant Quartermaster in Louisiana January 1864, accompanied the regiment to Virginia in July, and saw action at Opequon and Cedar Creek. He was promoted Captain in February 1865, resigned three months later, and returned home. His quartermaster invoices for 1864 survive at the Vermont Historical Society."},{"number":3,"category":"legacy","header":"Built the 1889 Queen Anne State Street mansion","body":"Edward commissioned a Queen Anne brick house at 120 State Street Montpelier in 1889 — designed by city mayor and architect George Guernsey on the site of his family's earlier home. The old house was moved to 144 State Street where it stood until 1969. Edward's 1889 house was moved to 128 State Street in 1948 to make way for the Vermont State Office Building."}],"cross_connections":[],"naming_inspiration":[],"education":[],"career":[{"role":"Mercantile (apprentice)","organization":"Various Vermont firms","end_year":1860,"notes":"Prepared for college but chose mercantile life until 1860."},{"role":"Assistant Secretary","organization":"Vermont Mutual Fire Insurance Co.","start_year":1860,"end_year":1864,"notes":"Four-year tenure before Civil War service."},{"role":"Assistant Secretary, then Vice-President","organization":"National Life Insurance Company","start_year":1865,"end_year":1897,"notes":"Returned from Civil War and joined NLI under his father's presidency. Elected vice-president June 1877; held position to January 1897."}],"military_service":[{"war":"American Civil War","rank":"Captain","rank_start":"Lieutenant","rank_end":"Captain","rank_year_start":1864,"rank_year_end":1865,"unit":"8th Regiment, Vermont Volunteer Infantry (Quartermaster)","notes":"Joined 8th VT Volunteers as Quartermaster in Louisiana January 1864; accompanied regiment to Virginia July 1864; participated in battles of Opequon and Cedar Creek. Promoted Captain and Assistant Quartermaster, U.S. volunteers staff department February 11, 1865; resigned three months later. Quartermaster papers preserved at Vermont Historical Society."}],"institutions":[{"institution_id":"INST112","relationship":"executive","years":"1865-1897","institution_blurb":"Civil War quartermaster who returned to serve as assistant secretary then vice-president of his father Julius's National Life Insurance Company until 1897."}],"landmarks":[{"landmark_id":"LM062","landmark_blurb":"Built the 1889 Queen Anne brick house at 120 State Street Montpelier (designed by mayor George Guernsey) on the site of his family home."}],"artworks":[],"documents":[],"quotes":[],"statues":[],"slug":"edward-dewey-1829"},"X02375":{"id":"X02375","former_ids":[],"is_placeholder":false,"has_descendants_documented":false,"bio":{"display_name":"Susan Griggs Lilley Dewey","first_name":"Susan","middle_name":"Griggs","last_name":"Dewey","maiden_name":"Lilley","married_names":["Dewey"]},"birth":{"year":1834,"month":10,"day":4,"city":"Sutton","county":"Worcester","state":"Massachusetts","country":"United States"},"baptism":{},"death":{"year":1909,"month":3,"day":22,"city":"Montpelier","county":"Washington","state":"Vermont","country":"United States"},"residence":{},"burial":{"cemetery_id":"CEM180","plot_notes":"Green Mount Cemetery, Montpelier VT."},"gender":"female","classification":{"include_in_path_calculation":false,"descent_from_thomas_hooker":false,"descent_from_john_talcott":false,"is_thomas_descendant":false,"is_talcott_descendant":false,"is_thomas_spouse":false,"is_talcott_spouse":true,"is_easter_egg":false,"descent_paths_to_thomas":0},"parents":{"father_research_notes":"Father Lilley (no further detail). Not built.","mother_research_notes":"Mother Susan Elizabeth Griggs (1816-1886) later became third wife of Edward's father Julius Yemans Dewey March 9, 1855 Montpelier VT — making Edward and Susan stepsiblings-by-marriage one year before they themselves married 1856. Not built."},"marriages":[{"marriage_number":1,"spouse_id":"TD0140","date_year":1856,"date_month":8,"date_day":27,"location_city":"Montpelier","location_state":"Vermont","location_country":"United States","end_type":"death_of_husband","end_year":1900,"children_ids":["TD0150","TD0151","TD0152","TD0153"]}],"number_of_marriages":1,"tags":[],"research_tags":[],"sources":[{"label":"FindAGrave — Susan Griggs Lilley Dewey","url":"https://www.findagrave.com/memorial/117096909/susan_griggs-dewey"}],"research_sources":[],"notable":{"is_notable":false,"notable_category":[]},"narrative_blocks":[],"cross_connections":[],"naming_inspiration":[],"education":[],"career":[],"military_service":[],"institutions":[],"landmarks":[],"artworks":[],"documents":[],"quotes":[],"statues":[],"slug":"susan-lilley-1834"},"X02373":{"id":"X02373","former_ids":[],"is_placeholder":false,"has_descendants_documented":false,"bio":{"display_name":"Doctor Julius Yemans Dewey","first_name":"Julius","middle_name":"Yemans","last_name":"Dewey","title":"Doctor","married_names":[],"photo_url":"https://res.cloudinary.com/dc5clrqtw/image/upload/v1777670388/juliusdewey_zbva4v.jpg","photo_notes":"Portrait. Cloudinary."},"birth":{"year":1801,"month":8,"day":22,"city":"Berlin","county":"Washington","state":"Vermont","country":"United States"},"baptism":{},"death":{"year":1877,"month":5,"day":29,"city":"Montpelier","county":"Washington","state":"Vermont","country":"United States"},"residence":{"city":"Montpelier","county":"Washington","state":"Vermont","country":"United States"},"burial":{"cemetery_id":"CEM180","plot_notes":"Green Mount Cemetery, Montpelier VT — Latitude 44.257843, Longitude -72.5944519."},"gender":"male","classification":{"include_in_path_calculation":false,"descent_from_thomas_hooker":false,"descent_from_john_talcott":false,"is_thomas_descendant":false,"is_talcott_descendant":false,"is_thomas_spouse":false,"is_talcott_spouse":true,"is_easter_egg":false,"descent_paths_to_thomas":0},"parents":{"father_research_notes":"Father Capt. Simeon Dewey (1770-1863), born Hebron CT, settled Berlin VT four miles from Montpelier, lived to age 93. m. Prudence Yemans (1772-1844) on February 27, 1794. Not built — non-tree.","mother_research_notes":"Mother Prudence Yemans Dewey (1772-1844). Not built — non-tree."},"marriages":[{"marriage_number":1,"spouse_id":"TD0138","date_year":1825,"date_month":6,"date_day":9,"location_city":"Berlin","location_state":"Vermont","location_country":"United States","end_type":"death_of_spouse","end_year":1843,"children_ids":["TD0139","TD0140","TD0141","TD0142"]}],"number_of_marriages":1,"tags":["physician"],"research_tags":[],"sources":[{"label":"Wikipedia — Julius Yemans Dewey","url":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Julius_Yemans_Dewey"},{"label":"FindAGrave — Dr Julius Yemans Dewey","url":"https://www.findagrave.com/memorial/117090576/julius_yemans-dewey"},{"label":"Vermont Historical Society — Dr. Julius Yemans Dewey portrait","url":"https://hub.catalogit.app/vermont-historical-society/folder/entry/dr.-julius-yemans-dewey"}],"research_sources":[],"notable":{"is_notable":true,"notable_category":["medicine","business","religion"],"notable_blurb":"Vermont physician; founded National Life Insurance","primary_url":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Julius_Yemans_Dewey","primary_url_label":"Wikipedia"},"narrative_blocks":[{"number":1,"category":"business","header":"Founded Vermont's largest life insurance company","body":"Julius founded the National Life Insurance Company at Montpelier in 1850 and served as its president until his death twenty-seven years later. He personally delivered the remittance for the company's first claim, prompting a public thank-you from the surviving family. NLI remains one of the ten oldest insurance companies in the United States."},{"number":2,"category":"family","header":"Married three Susans and one Mary Perrin","body":"After his Berlin sweetheart Mary Polly Perrin died in 1843 leaving four young children, Julius married twice more — both wives named Susan, neither bore him children. His third wife Susan Elizabeth Griggs Lilley had a daughter from a prior marriage who later married Julius's own son Edward — making Edward and his stepsister-in-law husband and wife."},{"number":3,"category":"character","header":"Backed his son's beating from Pangborn the teacher","body":"When eleven-year-old George Dewey led an attack on his Montpelier schoolteacher Z.K. Pangborn — and Pangborn flogged the boys into submission with a stick of stove fuel and walked the bruised George home to explain — Julius listened gravely, then thanked the teacher and asked him to repeat the punishment whenever necessary. George later credited the discipline with saving him from prison."}],"cross_connections":[],"naming_inspiration":[],"education":[{"school_name":"Washington County Grammar School","type":"secondary","notes":"Montpelier VT preparatory study."},{"school_name":"American Literary Scientific and Military Academy (Norwich Military School)","type":"military","notes":"Norwich Military School (later Norwich University) attended pre-medical."},{"school_name":"University of Vermont Medical Department","dates":"graduated 1824","type":"medical","notes":"M.D. class of 1824."}],"career":[{"role":"Physician (general practice)","organization":"Self / private practice","location":"Montpelier, Vermont","start_year":1824,"end_year":1851,"notes":"Practiced as 'most prominent practitioner and one of the leading citizens of the capital of Vermont' until founding NLI."},{"role":"Surgeon","organization":"First Regiment, Vermont State Militia","location":"Vermont"},{"role":"Founder and President","organization":"National Life Insurance Company","location":"Montpelier, Vermont","start_year":1850,"end_year":1877,"notes":"Founded 1850 (some sources 1848). Personally delivered the company's first claim remittance, prompting public thank-you from surviving family. Served as president until his death."},{"role":"Trustee","organization":"Norwich University","location":"Northfield, Vermont","end_year":1877},{"role":"Founder and parishioner","organization":"Christ Episcopal Church (Montpelier VT)","notes":"Documented founder of Christ Episcopal of Montpelier."}],"military_service":[],"institutions":[{"institution_id":"INST112","relationship":"founder","years":"1850-1877","institution_blurb":"Founder and president of the National Life Insurance Company of Montpelier — Vermont's largest life insurer."},{"institution_id":"INST113","relationship":"trustee","institution_blurb":"Trustee of Norwich University; previously attended its predecessor American Literary Scientific and Military Academy."}],"landmarks":[],"artworks":[{"artwork_id":"ART052","role":"subject","blurb":"Vermont Historical Society oil portrait c.1860, gift of Susan Howland estate."}],"documents":[],"quotes":[],"statues":[],"slug":"julius-dewey-1801"},"TD0138":{"id":"TD0138","former_ids":[],"is_placeholder":false,"has_descendants_documented":true,"bio":{"display_name":"Mary Polly Perrin Dewey","first_name":"Mary","middle_name":"Polly","last_name":"Dewey","maiden_name":"Perrin","married_names":["Dewey"],"photo_url":"https://res.cloudinary.com/dc5clrqtw/image/upload/v1777670322/marydewey_uh1h5i.jpg","photo_notes":"Portrait. Cloudinary."},"birth":{"year":1799,"month":1,"day":30,"city":"Berlin","county":"Washington","state":"Vermont","country":"United States"},"baptism":{},"death":{"year":1843,"month":9,"day":30,"city":"Montpelier","county":"Washington","state":"Vermont","country":"United States"},"residence":{"city":"Montpelier","county":"Washington","state":"Vermont","country":"United States"},"burial":{"cemetery_id":"CEM180","plot_notes":"Green Mount Cemetery, Montpelier VT — alongside Julius."},"gender":"female","classification":{"include_in_path_calculation":true,"descent_from_thomas_hooker":false,"descent_from_john_talcott":true,"is_thomas_descendant":false,"is_talcott_descendant":true,"is_thomas_spouse":false,"is_talcott_spouse":false,"generation_from_john_talcott":7,"is_easter_egg":false,"descent_paths_to_thomas":0},"parents":{"father_id":"X01832","mother_id":"T01387"},"marriages":[{"marriage_number":1,"spouse_id":"X02373","date_year":1825,"date_month":6,"date_day":9,"location_city":"Berlin","location_state":"Vermont","location_country":"United States","end_type":"death_of_self","end_year":1843,"children_ids":["TD0139","TD0140","TD0141","TD0142"]}],"number_of_marriages":1,"tags":["replacement_naming"],"research_tags":[],"sources":[{"label":"FindAGrave — Mary Polly Perrin Dewey","url":"https://www.findagrave.com/memorial/117090641/mary_polly-dewey"}],"research_sources":[],"notable":{"is_notable":false,"notable_category":[]},"narrative_blocks":[{"number":1,"category":"character","header":"Burned the log cabin where she was born","body":"Per family lore, Mary Polly was 'ashamed of having been born in a log cabin' — she and a sister later went up one night and burned the original Perrin cabin to the ground. Her father Zachariah's permanent farm at Scott Hill in Berlin Vermont stood on the same land, but the dirt-floor structure of her birth was gone by her own hand."},{"number":2,"category":"family","header":"Mother of Manila Bay's Admiral, died at forty-four","body":"Mary Polly bore Admiral George Dewey on December 26, 1837 — her third child. He was five years old when she died at age 44 in September 1843 Montpelier Vermont. Her husband Julius later married twice more, but Mary Polly was the mother of all his children."}],"cross_connections":[],"naming_inspiration":[{"name_element":"Mary","description":"Named for her elder sister Mary Perrin (1781-1798), born Hebron CT, who died at age seventeen — four months before her parents named the second baby Mary in her memory. The second Mary was sometimes called Polly to distinguish from her dead namesake."}],"education":[],"career":[],"military_service":[],"institutions":[],"landmarks":[],"artworks":[],"documents":[],"quotes":[],"statues":[],"slug":"mary-dewey-1799"}},"burialCemetery":{"id":"CEM044","name":"Arlington National Cemetery","city":"Arlington","county":"Arlington","state":"Virginia","country":"United States","lat":38.8769,"lng":-77.0733,"visitable":true,"notes":"National military cemetery. Burial place of Dr. John Minor (HD2760), WW1 veteran. Absorbed duplicate CEM475 Stage 6Y-691 per compiler ruling; the nation’s preeminent military cemetery — every attached ID verified retained in the merge audit.","sources":[],"hooker_connections":["HD0338","HD1206","HD1691","HD1759","HD2561","HD2563","HD2760","HD3015","HD3127","HD3850","HD3858","HD3916","HD4045","I00479","I00484","I00517","TD0150","X00385","X00569","X00855","X02053","X02071","X02091","I00696","HD5258","HD5858","I01512","HD6282","X03